Increasing probability in the 750 to 800 range as the recent daily increase has been between 3 to 4 TWh even with Nord Stream 1 shut down for maintenance. With 14-days to go (based on data from 17 July), a current starting point of 715.65, and an daily range between 3 and 4 (as a base case), the range is between 757 TWh and 771 TWh.

Tend puts it around 770. There are downside risks to the trend given Russia's desire for negotiating leverage this winter and upside given Europe's desire for the opposite. But history shows that trends are pretty stable based on the season.
Data from Monday and Tuesday has been updated.
Data from Tuesday shows a significant reduction of the accumulation rate. The average is 1.42 TWh/day during the first two days of the planned maintenance.

The current 10 day halt to the gas deliveries via Nord Stream 1 was scheduled, and took place also during 2021 and 2020 in the same period.

Gentle Heads up: There seems to have been a level shift in the 'Gas in Storage TWh" from the data source between 7 July and 8 July from 675 to 516 TWh. I have ask for clarification. For the below forecast, I am going to assume the data prior to 8 July is accurate.
Revising this forecast as read it wrong previous as a 2023 closure!
Recalculated. Season movements show that increase in storage increases until Oct. The daily increase could be higher, possibly 3 to 4 TWh per day.

Extending average daily increase from last period into the future gives 672 TWh at daily increase of some 0.36% per day, would lead to ca 737 Twh at 31 July. However, there are some political issues with storing gas, and GazProm owns at least part of the storage capacity which they can call on at any time, so it cannot easily be used by other owners. So, there remains a chance that the average daily increase will decline.
Current rate would put the value at the end of July at around 760-770 TWh.

Looking at a couple of years previous to the Covid pandemic it looks like storage around in July 650 was typical, which is around where it is now (646).
670 to 860 seems to be a plausible range. I'm thinking to spread out my probabilities even more.
Gas in storage currently at 639.9.

~60% capacity utilization in US. Must be 80% by November. July 31 means there's still Aug, Sept, Oct, so 3 months. At current +0.39 rate, would hit 80% by end of Aug, but given there exists costs to store gas I imagine the procurement should be at least the same pace for now given the conflict doesn't seem to be worsening.
misread data when updating earlier today, reverting closer to my initial forecast (https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1473050).
Seems to be gaining 30 TWh per week, meaning around +120TWh by end of July or 759TWh. Storage rate seems to be slowing as the EU's sanctions on itself hit.

The EU is aiming for 80% (~885TWh) gas storage by this winter, which seems to be defined as starting November 1 (https://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2022/06/27/council-adopts-regulation-gas-storage/), and is currently increasing their current storage (630TWh, 56.97% of full) by a bit under 30TWh per week.
avg increase over last month has been 28.579TWh - using that as baseline out next 5 weeks - would be 773TWh - not accounting for any weather or changes in geopolitical situation that might influence
